 Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rocliffe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Rawcliffe  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rawcliffe","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places in Lancashire, Yorkshire, and Cumbria called Rawcliffe or Rockcliffe. In most cases the placename is derived from Old Norse <i>rauthr</i> ‘red’ + <i>klif</i> ‘cliff, steep hill’. One in Lancashire is probably from Old English <i>rā</i> ‘roe deer’ + <i>clif</i> ‘cliff, steep hill’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":38,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":111,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Rocliffe was born about 1344, in Roecliffe, Yorkshire, England. She had at least 4 sons with Sir Richard Rocliffe."},"et":{"abt 1344–":"umbes 1344–Surnud","1342–Male":"1342–Surnud","1366–Male":"1366–Surnud","1368–1381":"1368–1381","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1372–Male":"1372–Surnud","1344–Female":"1344–Surnud","Abt 1368":"umbes 1368","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1381":